'''Tsuchimikado Yasukuni''' (土御門 泰邦) was a mid-[[Edo period]] nobleman and {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽家|12=draft|12=draft}}. He was the youngest son of {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasufuku|ja|土御門泰福|12=draft|12=draft}} and later adopted by his elder brother {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuren|ja|土御門泰連|12=draft|12=draft}}. He held the court rank of {{ill|Senior Second Rank|ja|正二位|1=Senior Second Rank|12=draft|12=draft}} and served as {{ill|Ministry of Ceremonies (Japan)|ja|治部卿|lt=Ministry of Ceremonies|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Career ==

Yasukuni's elder brother {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasei|ja|泰誠|12=draft|12=draft}}, the heir of their father Yasufuku, predeceased their father. Consequently, Yasuren inherited the family estate but remained childless. Yasukuni was adopted by Yasuren, inheriting the family on the condition that Yasuren’s biological son, {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yakei|ja|泰兄|12=draft|12=draft}}, would later succeed him.<ref>Yakei and his son {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yūhō|ja|土御門有邦|12=draft|12=draft}} predeceased Yasukuni. {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yashinobu|ja|土御門泰信|12=draft|12=draft}}, adopted from the {{ill|Hagiwara family|ja|萩原家|12=draft|12=draft}}, was later dismissed, and {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuaki|ja|土御門泰栄|12=draft|12=draft}}, a descendant of the Kurahashi branch and Yasukuni’s great-grandson, became his son-in-law and successor.</ref>

In {{ill|Kanen|ja|寛延|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1750), Yasukuni assumed his elder brother's rank of {{ill|Junior Third Rank|ja|従三位|1=Junior Third Rank|12=draft|12=draft}}.

During the Edo period, the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|12=draft|12=draft}} monopolized the authority to revise the calendar, stripping it from the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|朝廷|12=draft|12=draft}}. Yasukuni supported independent calendrical scholars like {{ill|Nishimura Enri|ja|西村遠里|12=draft|12=draft}} to challenge this. The 8th {{ill|shōgun|ja|征夷大将軍|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokugawa Yoshimune|ja|徳川吉宗|12=draft|12=draft}}, attempted to revise the calendar using Western astronomy but passed away, leaving the initiative incomplete. Yasukuni capitalized on this to lead the creation of the {{ill|Hōryaku calendar|ja|宝暦暦|12=draft|12=draft}}, implemented in {{ill|Hōryaku|ja|宝暦|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1755).

Although this earned him the title {{ill|Senior Second Rank|ja|正二位|1=Senior Second Rank|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Minister of Civil Affairs|ja|治部卿|12=draft|12=draft}}, inaccuracies in predicting {{ill|solar eclipses|ja|日食|12=draft|12=draft}} emerged soon after, prompting further revisions in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|12=draft|12=draft}} 8 (1771). Yasukuni's {{ill|Hōryaku calendar|ja|宝暦暦|12=draft|12=draft}} was replaced by the {{ill|Kansei calendar|ja|寛政暦|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kansei|ja|寛政|12=draft|12=draft}} 9 (1797), only 13 years after his death.

== Legacy ==

Yasukuni authored {{ill|Rokoku I|ja|漏刻緯|12=draft|12=draft}}, a study of {{ill|clepsydras|ja|漏刻|12=draft|12=draft}}, and contributed to the {{ill|Hōryaku Calendar Compendium|ja|宝暦暦法新書|12=draft|12=draft}}, though the clepsydras he attempted to reconstruct were flawed.<ref>Kinoshita Masashi, "Research and Clepsydras in the Edo Period," Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 2020, ISBN 978-4-642-04657-2, pp. 57, 59–63, 71.</ref>

He was interred at {{ill|Bairinji|ja|梅林寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in Kyoto, alongside other {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|12=draft|12=draft}} members, though no family contact remains.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Graves of Abe no Seimei’s Descendants at Risk|url=https://www.kyoto-np.co.jp/local/article/20170211000098|newspaper=Kyoto Shimbun|date=February 11, 2017}}</ref>

== Works ==

In {{ill|Hōryaku|ja|宝暦|12=draft|12=draft}} 10 (1760), Yasukuni recorded his journey to Edo in {{ill|Tōgyō Wasetsu|ja|東行話説|12=draft|12=draft}}, which offers insights into the culinary culture of the Tōkaidō.

== Lineage ==

* Father: {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasufuku|ja|土御門泰福|12=draft|12=draft}} (1655–1717)
* Mother: Unknown
* Foster Father: {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuren|ja|土御門泰連|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Wife: Unknown
* Daughter: Married to {{ill|Takatsuji Fukunaga|ja|高辻福長|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Adopted Son: {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yakei|ja|泰兄|12=draft|12=draft}}

