'''Tsuchimikado Yasukuni''' (土御門 泰邦) was a mid-[[Edo period]] nobleman and {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōji|qq=}}. He was the youngest son of {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasufuku|ja|土御門泰福|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yasufuku|qq=}} and later adopted by his elder brother {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuren|ja|土御門泰連|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yasuren|qq=}}. He held the court Rank of {{ill|Senior Second Rank|ja|正二位|1=Senior Second Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Second Rank|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Second Rank|qq=}} and served as {{ill|Ministry of Ceremonies (Japan)|ja|治部卿|lt=Ministry of Ceremonies|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ministry of Ceremonies (Japan)|qq=}}.

== Career ==

Yasukuni's elder brother {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasei|ja|泰誠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yasei|qq=}}, the heir of their father Yasufuku, predeceased their father. Consequently, Yasuren inherited the family estate but remained childless. Yasukuni was adopted by Yasuren, inheriting the family on the condition that Yasuren’s biological son, {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yakei|ja|泰兄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yakei|qq=}}, would later succeed him.<ref>Yakei and his son {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yūhō|ja|土御門有邦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yūhō|qq=}} predeceased Yasukuni. {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yashinobu|ja|土御門泰信|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yashinobu|qq=}}, adopted from the {{ill|Hagiwara family|ja|萩原家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hagiwara family|qq=}}, was later dismissed, and {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuaki|ja|土御門泰栄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yasuaki|qq=}}, a descendant of the Kurahashi branch and Yasukuni’s great-grandson, became his son-in-law and successor.</ref>

In {{ill|Kanen|ja|寛延|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanen|qq=}} 3 (1750), Yasukuni assumed his elder brother's Rank of {{ill|Junior Third Rank|ja|従三位|1=Junior Third Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Third Rank|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Third Rank|qq=}}.

During the Edo period, the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa shogunate|qq=}} monopolized the authority to revise the calendar, stripping it from the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|朝廷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court|qq=}}. Yasukuni supported independent calendrical scholars like {{ill|Nishimura Enri|ja|西村遠里|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishimura Enri|qq=}} to challenge this. The 8th {{ill|shōgun|ja|征夷大将軍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/shōgun|qq=}}, {{ill|Tokugawa Yoshimune|ja|徳川吉宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Yoshimune|qq=}}, attempted to revise the calendar using Western astronomy but passed away, leaving the initiative incomplete. Yasukuni capitalized on this to lead the creation of the {{ill|Hōryaku calendar|ja|宝暦暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōryaku calendar|qq=}}, implemented in {{ill|Hōryaku|ja|宝暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōryaku|qq=}} 5 (1755).

Although this earned him the title {{ill|Senior Second Rank|ja|正二位|1=Senior Second Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Second Rank|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Second Rank|qq=}} and {{ill|Minister of Civil Affairs|ja|治部卿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minister of Civil Affairs|qq=}}, inaccuracies in predicting {{ill|solar eclipses|ja|日食|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/solar eclipses|qq=}} emerged soon after, prompting further revisions in {{ill|Meiwa|ja|明和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiwa|qq=}} 8 (1771). Yasukuni's {{ill|Hōryaku calendar|ja|宝暦暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōryaku calendar|qq=}} was replaced by the {{ill|Kansei calendar|ja|寛政暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kansei calendar|qq=}} in {{ill|Kansei|ja|寛政|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kansei|qq=}} 9 (1797), only 13 years after his death.

== Legacy ==

Yasukuni authored {{ill|Rokoku I|ja|漏刻緯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokoku I|qq=}}, a study of {{ill|clepsydras|ja|漏刻|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/clepsydras|qq=}}, and contributed to the {{ill|Hōryaku Calendar Compendium|ja|宝暦暦法新書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōryaku Calendar Compendium|qq=}}, though the clepsydras he attempted to reconstruct were flawed.<ref>Kinoshita Masashi, "Research and Clepsydras in the Edo Period," Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 2020, ISBN 978-4-642-04657-2, pp. 57, 59–63, 71.</ref>

He was interred at {{ill|Bairinji|ja|梅林寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bairinji|qq=}} in Kyoto, alongside other {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}} members, though no family contact remains.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Graves of Abe no Seimei’s Descendants at Risk|url=https://www.kyoto-np.co.jp/local/article/20170211000098|newspaper=Kyoto Shimbun|date=February 11, 2017}}</ref>

== Works ==

In {{ill|Hōryaku|ja|宝暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōryaku|qq=}} 10 (1760), Yasukuni recorded his journey to Edo in {{ill|Tōgyō Wasetsu|ja|東行話説|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōgyō Wasetsu|qq=}}, which offers insights into the culinary culture of the Tōkaidō.

== Lineage ==

* Father: {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasufuku|ja|土御門泰福|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yasufuku|qq=}} (1655–1717)
* Mother: Unknown
* Foster Father: {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yasuren|ja|土御門泰連|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yasuren|qq=}}
* Wife: Unknown
* Daughter: Married to {{ill|Takatsuji Fukunaga|ja|高辻福長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takatsuji Fukunaga|qq=}}
* Adopted Son: {{ill|Tsuchimikado Yakei|ja|泰兄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Yakei|qq=}}

